> 'Dirty Rice' is usually associated with Cajun cooking and takes its name from the colour of the rice once it's mixed with meat and spices. We've given the dish a Mexican spin by using chorizo, paprika and black beans and balancing them with lime, tomatoes and coriander to create something really zingy and fresh. It seems you can't always judge a book by its cover!

Boil a large #pot{} of water on high heat with @salt{1/4%tsp} for your rice. Rinse the @Basmati Rice{1%cup} under running water for ~{30%seconds} and then add to the rapidly boiling water. Cook the rice for around ~{25%mins} until it is soft then drain and keep to the side and allow to cool slightly.

Peel and finely dice the @onion{1/2}. Cut the @cherry tomatoes{1/2%cup} into quarters. Roughly chop the @coriander{3%sprigs}. Rinse and drain the @organic black beans{1%can}. Chop the @green pepper{1/2} into 1cm pieces.

Mix the @smoked paprika{1%tsp} with the zest of a one third of the @lime{1/2}, @salt{1/4%tsp}, @ground black pepper{some} and @olive oil{1 1/2%tbsp}. Cut the @British chicken thighs{2} into bite sized pieces and coat in the spice mix.

Heat a #frying pan{} over a medium-high heat with @olive oil{1%tbsp} and cook the green pepper for ~{3%mins}. Remove and cook the @diced chorizo{1%cup} and onion for ~{5%mins} or until the chorizo is crispy, then also remove from the pan. Add the chicken to the (now empty) pan and cook for ~{5-8%mins} until cooked through.

> Cook the chicken in two batches to make sure you get this nice and brown.

In a large #bowl{}, mix the cooked rice, chorizo, onion, tomatoes, black beans and pepper with the cooked chicken and two thirds of your chopped coriander. Make a dressing with the remaining zest and juice of the lime, @salt{1/4%tsp}, @ground black pepper{some} and @olive oil{1%tbsp} and mix with the rice salad.

> You can replace the olive oil with the pan juices from the chorizo and chicken.

Divide the rice between your #bowls{}, sprinkle over the remaining coriander and tuck in!